<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence submitted by Achievement for All 3As</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">OAR0010</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">evidence submitted by Achievement for All 3As</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction to Achievement for All 3As</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 29.21pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Achievement for All (3As) Ltd is an independent charity, established in May 2011, with the mission to transform the lives of vulnerable children, young people and their families, by raising their educational aspirations, access and achievement.  The charity is led by its Chair,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><a href="http://www.afa3as.org.uk/the-charity/trustees/brian-lamb"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Brian Lamb</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">OBE</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, author of the Lamb Inquiry on Special Educational Needs (SEN) and Parental Confidence, and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><a href="http://www.afa3as.org.uk/the-charity/afa-3as-team/professor-sonia-blandford"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Professor Sonia </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Blandford</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, CEO and National Director of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DfE</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> funded Achievement for All programme.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 29.21pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There are currently c.2000 schools (primary, secondary, special and pupil referral units) involved in the Achievement for All programme. The Impact Assessment </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in 2012/2013</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(PwC, 2013) showed pupil Average Point Scores (in reading, writing and maths) 50% above national results for SEN pupils (national expectation is 4 APS pa). Changes in teaching and learning ran concurrent with this; there was an 11% improvement in the ‘effective use of teaching practices’ and an equal 11% increase in teacher confidence in teaching pupils with SEN. The Charity is also developing and delivering a number of other innovative interventions for schools in the UK and internationally to improve outcomes of disadvantaged children, those with SEN</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">D</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and other vulnerable children. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Submission to the Education Committee – Inquiry into Ofsted Annual Report in Education 2012-2013: </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Executive Summary</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 29.21pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In broad terms, Achievement for All 3As supports a framework in schools where </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">all vulnerable and disadvantaged children and young people can develop their skills, interests and capabilities to achieve. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 29.21pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Achievement for All welcomes this opportunity to provide a response to the Education Committee on the inquiry into Ofsted Annual Report in Education 2012-2013. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Achievement for All 3As response to Ofsted Annual Report in Education 2012-2013: </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 29.21pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Driving whole school improvement is about improving expectations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, an essential tenet of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Achievement for All</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> framework (leadership, teaching and learning, parents and wider outcomes)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and relationships overall, not just leaders but a combination of top down and bottom up engagement and support.  Offering challenge without support is not necessarily helpful.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 29.21pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">For schools, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">change </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">involves a focus on raising aspirations (teachers, parents and pupils), increasing access and increasing achievement. This is done through effective deployment of resources- leadership, quality teaching and learning, parental and carer engagement in children’s learning and behaviour and attendance. This mirrors the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Achievement for All</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> programme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In 2012, schools engaged in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Achievement for All</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> programme saw Average Point Score increases of 50% above the national average for pupils with SEN; for reading and writing the increase was 4.2 APS. For maths this figure was an increase of 3.8 APS. Findings across schools also showed a 17% improvement in parent and carer engagement with teachers and with their children’s learning; there was a 36% increase in schools reporting excellent relationships with parents and carers. In top performing  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Achievement for All</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> schools, i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ncreases of up to 330% in Average Point Scores of between 6.50 and 9.15 in reading, writing and math were found. Student behaviour and attendance improved with a 9% improvement in student attendance and an 8% improvement in student behaviour. (PwC, 2013).</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 29.21pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The report from Michael </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Wilshaw</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, Her Majesty’s Chief Inspector of Education, claims that there remains a battle against mediocrity in many of England’s schools and in particular focuses on poor teaching and weak leadership, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">regional variations in the quality of education provision, and the under achievement of children from low income families, particularly White children. Almost 2000 schools across the country are now engaged with Achievement for All 3As, improving progress for vulnerable and disadvantaged pupils. Skilled locally-based Achievement Coaches support leadership and development throughout the school so that all teaching professionals are enabled to deliver high quality teaching, work with parents and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">carers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to engage in their child’s education, and ensure that pupils have the appropriate </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">behaviour</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> for learning. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 29.21pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In high performing education systems there is greater equity; all children are provided with the opportunity for ‘quality’ education (OECD, 2012). Schools nationally need to focus on raising the achievement of all children. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 29.21pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Many of the recent educational reforms have led to increased pupil attainment and progress. The government supports the national expansion of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Achievement for All</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. Government still has a strong role to play in ensuring that there is equity and quality in education for every child. This includes promoting a culture of high expectations across all schools</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (involving</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> school leaders, teachers, other relevant professionals, parents and carers, children and young people)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and a focus nationally on educational outcomes of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">pupils with SEND, looked after children, those eligible for free school meals and other vulnerable and disadvantaged learners. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">January 2014</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Appendix 1</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Key findings from Achievement for All pilot (2009-2011) (Humphrey and Squires, 2011)</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">454 primary, secondary and special schools and pupil referral units across 10 local authorities in England participated in the Achievement for All pilot, with a cohort of 28,000 pupils. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Key findings showed that:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">37% of SEND pupils in Achievement for All pilot schools achieved or exceeded expected levels of progress in English compared to ALL pupils nationally.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">42% of SEND pupils in the Achievement for All schools achieved or exceeded expected levels of progress in Maths compared to all pupils nationally.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A 10% drop in persistent absenteeism across schools.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The number of Achievement for All schools reporting that they now have excellent relationships with parents increased by 36%.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">1</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>